<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,554,844]" box="[151,270,554,579]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis box="[151,270,554,579]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,554,844]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[407,498,592,618]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" unit="mm" value="21.0">21 mm</quantity>
. The species is similar to S. 
<taxonomicName box="[862,950,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Scobura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coniata">
<emphasis box="[862,950,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">coniata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be separated by the following characters: forewing upperside cell spots separated, subequal; spot in space CuA 
<number box="[1126,1134,645,659]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1.0">1</number>
rather narrow; without a linear stigma in male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,554,844]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[393,544,706,732]" captionStart="FIGURES 48 − 52" captionStartId="8.[151,270,1455,1479]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,901,1427]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,901,1431]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 48 − 52. Male genitalia of Scobura lyso (Evans) (Zhejiang). 48. ring, lateral view; 49. tegumen, dorsal view; 50. valva, inner view; 51. aedeagus; 52. juxta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195597/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Figs. 
<number box="[464,544,706,732]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="50.0" valueMax="52.0" valueMin="48.0">48−52</number>
</figureCitation>
): Tegumen without socius; valva nearly rectangular, ventrodistal process equal to about half length of valva, with upper margin straight and armed with spines, dorsobasal process very long, thin and sharp spine; aedeagus with suprazonal sheath slightly shorter than subzonal sheath; juxta Ushaped with two densely spined arms.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
