<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1826,1964]" box="[151,254,1826,1851]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis box="[151,254,1826,1851]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1826,1964]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The species had been treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName box="[788,876,1864,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Scobura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coniata">
<emphasis box="[788,876,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">coniata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
until 
<bibRefCitation author="Devyatkin" box="[951,1162,1863,1889]" pageId="8" pageNumber="15" refString="Devyatkin, A. L. (2004) Taxonomic studies on Oriental Hesperiidae, 1. A revision of the Scobura coniata Hering, 1918 - group. Atalanta, 35 (1 / 2), 57 - 66." type="journal article" year="2004">
Devyatkin (
<number box="[1092,1154,1863,1889]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
revised the group and upgraded it to species status based on genitalic features. The shape of the valva and its dorsobasal process are quite distinct from related species.
</paragraph>
